    "narrative": "For Ghost Ride the WHIP\u2019s May 3rd slate, our strongest plays are concentrated in favorable right-handed matchups. **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) leads the charge; his synergy of a strong park factor and a massive +14% platoon edge against Strider makes him our premier start. **Seiya Suzuki** (69.12) is equally compelling, bolstered by an 87% stolen base success rate against the opposing pitcher\u2019s delivery, which aligns perfectly with our organizational priority on speed. Meanwhile, **Austin Riley** (66.95) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (64.77) anchor the heart of the order, with **Vinnie Pasquantino** specifically benefiting from a +14% platoon boost despite a neutral park environment. While **Corbin Carroll** (57.68) remains a staple, his production is hampered today by a pitcher who excels at neutralizing the running game (62% SB hold), forcing us to temper expectations for his total utility.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Cole Young** (42.74), who fell just shy of the threshold. While he possesses the sprint speed we covet, his marginal score against Bubic was ultimately outclassed by the higher floor provided by the middle-infield depth of **Travis Bazzana** (59.59). Elsewhere, we continue to monitor the status of **Max Muncy**, who remains sidelined on the IL, while **Trevor Story** and **Brice Turang** remain on the bench due to lack of confirmed lineup presence. We are also keeping a close eye on the volatile matchup for **James Wood** (52.10); while his leadoff spot and 0.381 xwOBA are encouraging, the -19% SP skill penalty suggests a high-variance day. With other bench assets like **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Carson Williams**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Kyle Karros**, and **Luis Campusano** also unavailable or underperforming relative to today's projected efficiency, our starting nine remains our most viable path to success.",
